+++ b/SECRETS.md
@@ -0,0 +1,58 @@
+# Setting up local secrets
+
+`appsettings.json` no longer contains real credentials — it's committed to
+git, and this repo is public, so anything placed there is public too.
+
+## ⚠️ Do this first, before anything else
+
+The Gmail app password and the `master123` super-admin password that used to
+be in `appsettings.json` are now **public** (they're visible in this repo's
+git history even after this fix). You must:
+
+1. Revoke that Gmail app password and generate a new one:
+   https://myaccount.google.com/apppasswords
+2. Change/rotate any account that used `master123` (or the same password
+   anywhere else).
+3. Ideally, scrub the old secrets from git history (e.g. with
+   [`git filter-repo`](https://github.com/newren/git-filter-repo) or the
+   [BFG Repo-Cleaner](https://rtyley.github.io/bfg-repo-cleaner/)) since
+   deleting the file in a new commit alone leaves the old values in history.
+
+## Local development — use `dotnet user-secrets`
+
+From the `SaleSync/` project folder:
+
+```bash
+dotnet user-secrets init
+dotnet user-secrets set "EmailSettings:SenderEmail" "you@example.com"
+dotnet user-secrets set "EmailSettings:Username" "you@example.com"
+dotnet user-secrets set "EmailSettings:Password" "your-new-gmail-app-password"
+
+dotnet user-secrets set "SuperAdminConfig:Username" "choose-a-username"
+```
+
+### Generating the super-admin password hash
+
+The super-admin password is now stored as a bcrypt hash, never plaintext.
+Generate one with a short throwaway script (run once, then delete):
+
+```csharp
+// hash.csx or a scratch Program.cs — requires BCrypt.Net-Next
+Console.WriteLine(BCrypt.Net.BCrypt.HashPassword("your-new-strong-password"));
+```
+
+Then:
+
+```bash
+dotnet user-secrets set "SuperAdminConfig:PasswordHash" "$2a$11$...the output..."
+```
+
+User-secrets are stored outside the repo (`%APPDATA%\Microsoft\UserSecrets`
+on Windows, `~/.microsoft/usersecrets` on Linux/Mac) and are never committed.
+
+## Production
+
+Don't use user-secrets in production. Use environment variables (ASP.NET
+Core config automatically maps `SuperAdminConfig__PasswordHash` etc. to the
+same keys) or a proper secret manager (Azure Key Vault, AWS Secrets Manager,
+etc.).
